Nov 5 2004 	Great stay...not sure what the issues are with others	I stayed at the Monarch three nights, October 28-30. I was a little worried after reading the reviews...but in all honesty for a tourist-class hotel it's a great bargin.I was able to check-in early and all my questions about the hotel and city were promptly and courteously answered. The room was very clean (among the cleanest I've stayed in). The decor was a little on the worn-side of things...but still nice. (This appears to be a fairly busy hotel...so a little ware is expected.) There are several good eats nearby....Mel's Diner, Maharani (some of the best Indian food I've every had), and lots of other places on VanNess. It's also within a short walk of all of the cultural arts venues (Davies Symphony Hall, War Memorial Opera Hall, the Asian Museum, etc....) Public transportation was plentiful with lots of choices nearby (taxi, bus, underground, etc...)One thing people should remember is that San Francisco is a pretty big city. There is going to be street noise...there are going to be homeless people...there are going to be adult bookstores....etc... This is just part of a big city. Just because you spend $250/night for a hotel in the city, doesn't mean you are going to get away from all of this. I've been to several other big US cities as well as European cities and have encountered all of this everywhere I've been. This is what makes a big city what it is.For less than $70/night....this is a steal. Clean, comfortable, affordable, good location...what else can you ask for? If you are looking for ultra-posh pampering, or aren't used to traveling in a big city...the Monarch isn't for you. If you are city-friendly and looking for a great deal....give the Monarch a try.	
Oct 31 2004	The Monarch Hotel makes decent budget option	I have been previously notified by my sister about the negatives to the hotel, but is glad to report that the hotel turned out to be pretty decent esp. for those on a budget.The room is rather smallish but managed to cramp in a built-in heater, table set, a really comfortable queen sized bed with cabled tv. It is not quite refined at the edges and shows a bit of age, but neither is anything falling apart and it is well kept. My main complaint will be the obscured power points behind the bed and television that makes plugging in the room a hassle, but this is not difficult to overcome.The staffs at the hotel can come across as impersonal and unfriendly, though they are professional and will assist promptly when required. There is also free wireless internet access in the lobby, but this can be spotty at times.A genuine concern will be the location of the hotel. Near where it is called Tenderloin, the area around can be rather unsettling with panhandlers, drunks and homeless people hanging around esp. at night. But as long as they are politely rejected or ignored, we did not encounter any real harrassments or problems other than feeling jittery at times. It will however be wise to avoid walking southwards towards Civic Center at night. The hotel staffs are very quick at managing and turning away occasional unwanted guests, so once within the hotel premises security is maintained.	
